write a Python function to do a case insensitive sort of a list of strings
def csort(lst): 
    return sorted(set([s.lower() for s in lst]))


This will return the original input lists with all uppercase and lowercase letters converted to their corresponding single-character version, so that 'apple' becomes 'apl', which is then ordered alphabetically as a list of strings (in case there were multiple occurrences).
